#### 19. Proof by Ordeal.

\* 247. If no witness is forthcoming for either of the two litigant
parties, he must test them through ordeals and oaths of every sort.

\* 248. <span id="fr_292"></span>[248](#fn_292.md) (Let him cause a Brahman
to swear by) truth, (a Kshatriya) by his (horse or other) vehicle, and
by his weapons, (a Vai*s*ya) by his cows, seeds or gold and so on, (or
all) by venerable deities or deified ancestors, by their pious gifts or
meritorious deeds.

249. <span id="fr_293"></span>[249](#fn_293.md) Where a heavy crime has
been committed, the ruler shall administer one of the ordeals. In light
cases, on the other hand, a virtuous king shall swear a man with
(various) oaths.

\* 250. Thus have these oaths been proclaimed by Manu for trifling
cases. In a suit concerning a heavy crime, divine test should be
resorted to.

251. <span id="fr_294"></span>[251](#fn_294.md) Holy Manu has ordained that
five kinds of ordeals should be administered to those involved in a
doubtful case (which has become the object of a lawsuit), especially if
the matter under dispute is of a recondite nature.

\* 252. <span id="fr_295"></span>[252](#fn_295.md) The balance, fire,
water, poison, and, fifthly, consecrated water, are the ordeals ordained
for the purgation of high-minded persons.

<span id="page_101">p. 101</span>

\* 253. <span id="fr_296"></span>[253](#fn_296) (Those ordeals.md) have
been ordained here by Nârada for the purpose of proving the innocence of
criminals who are defendants in a lawsuit, (and) in order that right may
be discerned from wrong.

\* 254. <span id="fr_297"></span>[254](#fn_297.md) During the rains let the
(ordeal by) fire be administered. In the autumn season the balance is
declared to be (the proper kind of ordeal). The (ordeal by) water should
be applied in summer, and the (ordeal by) poison in the cold weather.

\* 255. <span id="fr_298"></span>[255](#fn_298.md) The distressed shall not
be caused to undergo the (ordeal by) water, nor shall poison be given to
the bilious, nor shall the ordeal by fire be administered to persons
afflicted with white leprosy, or with blindness, or with bad nails.

\* 256. <span id="fr_299"></span>[256](#fn_299.md) An ordeal should never
be administered to persons engaged in performing a vow, to those
afflicted with a heavy calamity, to the diseased, to ascetics, or to
women, if the dictates of justice are listened to.

257. <span id="fr_300"></span>[257](#fn_300.md) Where no one declares
himself ready to

<span id="page_102">p. 102</span>

undergo punishment, an ordeal cannot take place. An ordeal shall be
administered to litigants where there is reason for it, but not
otherwise.

258. <span id="fr_301"></span>[258](#fn_301.md) Therefore an intelligent,
virtuous, righteous, and wise (king or chief judge) should abstain
carefully from administering any one out of the (five) ordeals, unless
both parties consent to it.

\* 259. <span id="fr_302"></span>[259](#fn_302.md) The ordeal by water must
not take place in the cold weather, nor the ordeal by fire in the hot
season, nor must the (ordeal by) poison be administered to any one
during the rains, nor the (ordeal by) balance in stormy weather.

