### Footnotes

<span id="fn_292"></span>[100:248](sbe3326.htm#fr_292.md) In this rule are
indicated the various oaths to be administered according to the caste
and individual character of the offender. A. Manu VIII, 114.

<span id="fn_293"></span>[100:249](sbe3326.htm#fr_293.md) 249, 250. These
two verses are intended to indicate the difference in point of
applicability between an ordeal and an oath. A.

<span id="fn_294"></span>[100:251](sbe3326.htm#fr_294.md) Holy Manu has
said that those against whom a charge of an aggravated nature has been
brought, shall have to undergo one out of the five ordeals, in order to
clear themselves from suspicion, especially when a secret transgression
is concerned. A.

<span id="fn_295"></span>[100:252](sbe3326.htm#fr_295.md) In this paragraph
the author proceeds to enumerate the five ordeals singly. A.
Yâ*gñ*avalkya II, 95; Vish*n*u IX, II.

<span id="fn_296"></span>[101:253](sbe3326.htm#fr_296.md) The five ordeals
have been proclaimed by the great sage Nârada, for the justification of
those impeached on account of their suspicious conduct, by showing where
the wrong lies and where not. A.

<span id="fn_297"></span>[101:254](sbe3326.htm#fr_297.md) The five ordeals
should be administered, each of them, at those very seasons, and not at
any other season. A. Vish*n*u IX, 25, 28, 30.

<span id="fn_298"></span>[101:255](sbe3326.htm#fr_298.md) 255, 256.
Vish*n*u IX, 23, 25, 27, 29.

255\. In the case of the persons here mentioned, the ordeals referred to
should be avoided, on grounds of disease and of incapacity to undergo
them. A.

<span id="fn_299"></span>[101:256](sbe3326.htm#fr_299.md) 'Persons engaged
in performing a vow,' those who have performed the ceremony initiatory
to a Soma sacrifice. A.

<span id="fn_300"></span>[101:257](sbe3326.htm#fr_300.md) An ordeal should
not take place, unless there should be a special reason for it, such as
an accusation. Therefore an ordeal must not be administered, unless
there be a plaintiff who declares himself ready to take the punishment
on himself in case of defeat. <span id="page_102">p. 102</span> A.
Yâ*gñ*avalkya II, 96; Vish*n*u IV, 20, 21. The reading na divya*m* (for
na vinâ?) seems wrong. Or translate, 'but there is no ordeal for
plaintiffs.'

<span id="fn_301"></span>[102:258](sbe3326.htm#fr_301.md) A king or
chief-judge, who is endowed with the qualities here mentioned, should
administer an ordeal with the full approval of both parties in a cause,
but not otherwise. A.

<span id="fn_302"></span>[102:259](sbe3326.htm#fr_302.md) The times or
seasons here referred to should be avoided in the case of the ordeal by
water and of the other ordeals, because they are illegal. A. Vish*n*u
IX, 24, 26, 28, 30.

